# Keep the build context lean so it doesn't balloon (the repo ships ~4MB banner
# PNGs) and so cache doesn't bust on every unrelated edit. The Dockerfile copies
# the lockfile + manifests for `pnpm fetch`, then full source for the build; deps
# and build outputs are produced inside the image, never copied from the host.

# Dependencies — reinstalled in-image from the pnpm store.
node_modules
**/node_modules
.pnp
.pnp.js

# Build outputs — rebuilt by tsup in the build stage.
dist
**/dist
.next
**/.next
out
**/out
build

# Turbo / tooling caches.
.turbo
**/.turbo
coverage
**/coverage

# VCS + CI metadata.
.git
.github
.changeset

# Local env files — never bake secrets into the image.
.env
.env.*
**/.env
**/.env.*

# Tests are not needed in the runtime image.
**/__tests__
**/*.test.ts

# The root Go CLI dir is not a pnpm workspace member — drop it entirely.
cli

# Reference docs (the deployment plan etc.) are not needed in any build stage.
docs

# The docs site IS a pnpm workspace member, so its package.json must stay for
# `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` to validate the workspace. Drop only its
# (large) content; the manifest is re-included so the lockfile still resolves.
apps/docs
!apps/docs/package.json

# Heavy static assets (the ~4MB banner PNGs) and misc local files.
*.png
*.pem
*.log
.DS_Store
pgdata/
backups/
.hogsend.yaml

# Docker artifacts themselves.
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
docker-compose*.yml
